@lawrenceakka After looking at python-future, I tend to agree with you that it is probably the way to go. For one thing, it seems to be more about being able to write python 3 code that also works on earlier versions (than the other way around), which I really am a big fan of. It also seems like a well thought through project. There was a few things that initially worried me (which are actually many of the things they do more than six);
 1. When talking about more backports, one might of course worry about the quality of these backports, especially if in the code it looks the functions your're calling is the stdlib, but they have adopted a fair amount of tests from the standard library for that backported functionality, so that makes me a little more at ease.
 2. They also do a few things like shadowing builtin types, which I must admit, still makes a little uneasy. But the main author claims that it is actually "unproblematic" (http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KOqk8j11aAI&t=10m14s) and in any case I guess we decide for out selves which of the features we want to use.

All in all, I will recommend python-future as well. What do you think @stefankoegl and others?

